Predicting Tennis Match Outcomes: A Data-Driven Approach to the Game

Team: SNM Analytics

2023-05-02

Chapter 1: Introduction

Background to Tennis

Tennis is a global sport with admirers from all over the world. Tennis players arrived from all over the world, with varying playing styles and specializations. Every tennis match is defined by a plethora of variables, making the sport both entertaining and unexpected.The outcome of a match can be highly valuable for a variety of reasons, such as calculating the odds of bets or better arranging the season of sportsmen, who would undoubtedly be more interested in participating in competitions with higher chances of winning.

R Markdown Logo

Project Overview

Jeff Sackmann, an author and sports data aggregator, provided the dataset for this project. The dataset contains information on tennis matches from 1968 to 2023, with more extensive match statistics available starting from 1997. Following data processing, we tested various models for predicting match outcomes. To achieve our goal, we used a number of models ranging from Logistic Regression to SVM. Finally, after some fine-tuning of these models, we were able to create models that provided the best predictions. Our goal is to visualize the availability of match statistics and explore the data to understand its structure and contents.

Research Question:

Why is it critical to predict the outcome of a tennis match?

It is critical to determine the key factors that influence the outcome of a tennis match. Researchers and practitioners can develop better predictions about match outcomes by studying which aspects are most influential, which can inform strategy for coaches, players, and analysts. Identifying the most relevant aspects can also provide insights into the underlying dynamics of tennis matches, assisting in the creation of more successful training and coaching tactics.To answer this question, we have come up with a research question.

What are the most important features that influence the outcome of a tennis match, and how accurately can we predict the winner of a match using a machine learning model based on these features?

# Initialize an empty data frame
data <- data.frame()

# Loop through the years and read the corresponding atp_matches files
for (year in 1968:2023) {
  file_path <- paste0("data/atp_matches_", year, ".csv")
  if (file.exists(file_path)) {
    temp_data <- read.csv(file_path)
    data <- rbind(data, temp_data)
  }
}

Chapter 2: Dataset & EDA

The dataset contains information about tennis matches played between 1963 and 2023, with a total of 189,185 records. It includes 49 columns, which provide information about the players, match statistics, and other relevant details.

Dataset Description

Some of the key features in the dataset are:

  1. Player details: player names, ages, heights, etc.
  2. Match details: tournament name, surface, round, etc.
  3. Player rankings: ATP rankings and ranking points.
  4. Match statistics: aces, double faults, first serves in, first serve points won, etc.

Data Preprocessing

Data Cleaning

This code cleans data and conducts exploratory data analysis on a tennis match statistics dataset. The process starts by transforming a character column (tourney_date) into a Date object and extracting the year component into a new column (year). It then selects a selection of numeric columns from the dataset that contain match statistics and computes the percentage of non-null values every year for each column using the dplyr package’s mean() and across() functions. The resulting summary data is then gathered into a long format for easier charting using the gather() function. This code can help guide further studies and modeling efforts by finding trends and patterns in missing data for each match statistic over time.

# Convert tourney_date character type to a Date object
data$tourney_date <- as.Date(as.character(data$tourney_date), "%Y%m%d")

# Extract year from tourney_date
data$year <- year(data$tourney_date)

# Select the relevant columns (numeric match statistics)
stats_columns <- c("w_ace", "w_df", "w_svpt", "w_1stIn", "w_1stWon", "w_2ndWon", "w_SvGms", "w_bpSaved", "w_bpFaced",
                   "l_ace", "l_df", "l_svpt", "l_1stIn", "l_1stWon", "l_2ndWon", "l_SvGms", "l_bpSaved", "l_bpFaced")


# Calculate the percentage of non-null values per year for each numeric variable
non_null_stats <- data %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(across(all_of(stats_columns), ~mean(!is.na(.)) * 100, .names = "pct_non_null_{col}"))

# Gather the data into a long format for easy plotting
non_null_stats_long <- non_null_stats %>%
  gather(key = "variable", value = "pct_non_null", -year)
# Plot the percentage of non-null values per year for each numeric variable
ggplot(non_null_stats_long, aes(x = year, y = pct_non_null, color = variable)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Percentage of Non-Null Match Statistics per Year",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Percentage of Non-Null Values",
       color = "Statistic") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 10),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 8)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(non_null_stats_long$year), max(non_null_stats_long$year), by = 5))

# Analyze missing values in the dataset
missing_values <- data %>%
  gather(variable, value, -tourney_id, -tourney_name, -tourney_date, -match_num, -winner_id, -loser_id) %>%
  mutate(is_missing = is.na(value)) %>%
  group_by(variable) %>%
  summarize(missing_count = sum(is_missing), total_count = n(), missing_percentage = missing_count / total_count * 100)

# Create the box plot

  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

# Display the box plot
print(box_plot)

In tennis, “winner_first_serve_pct” typically refers to the percentage of first serves that a player won. It is calculated by dividing the number of first serve points won by the number of first serves that the player hit, and then multiplying by 100 to get a percentage.From the boxplot winner first serve winning percentage is quite higher than loser first serve percentage.

# suffling the data randomly as it is all sorted year by year
data <- data[sample(1:nrow(data)), ]
# Determine the number of rows in half the dataset
half_nrow <- nrow(data) %/% 2

# Split the dataset in half
first_half <- data[1:half_nrow, ]
second_half <- data[(half_nrow + 1):nrow(data), ]

# Rename columns for the first half
colnames(first_half)[grep("winner", colnames(first_half))] <- gsub("winner", "player0", colnames(first_half)[grep("winner", colnames(first_half))])
colnames(first_half)[grep("loser", colnames(first_half))] <- gsub("loser", "player1", colnames(first_half)[grep("loser", colnames(first_half))])

# Rename columns for the second half
colnames(second_half)[grep("winner", colnames(second_half))] <- gsub("winner", "player1", colnames(second_half)[grep("winner", colnames(second_half))])
colnames(second_half)[grep("loser", colnames(second_half))] <- gsub("loser", "player0", colnames(second_half)[grep("loser", colnames(second_half))])

# Add 'winner' column to the first half and set it to 0 (player0 is the winner)
first_half$winner <- 0

# Add 'winner' column to the second half and set it to 1 (player1 is the winner)
second_half$winner <- 1

# Combine the two halves
renamed_data <- rbind(first_half, second_half)
final_data <- read_csv("tennis_data.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

Modelling

Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a statistical modeling technique that uses one or more predictor variables to predict the likelihood of a binary outcome variable. When the dependent variable is categorical and binary (e.g., yes or no, 0 or 1, true or false), this sort of regression analysis is used.

The Variance Inflation Factor is a regression analysis metric that quantifies the degree of multicollinearity between predictor variables in a model. In other words, it quantifies the extent to which the variance of the predicted regression coefficients is exaggerated due to the presence of correlated factors.

Support Vector Machine

SVMs are a form of machine learning method that can be used for classification, regression, and outlier detection. SVM is a powerful and adaptable technique for modeling complex non-linear connections between variables.

Random Forest Model

Random forest is a machine learning technique that can be used for classification as well as regression. It is an ensemble learning method that makes predictions by combining numerous decision trees. A random subset of the training data and a random subset of the characteristics are used to build each decision tree. This adds unpredictability to the model and helps to avoid overfitting, a major issue with decision trees.

Chapter 4: Conclusion

The performance of three models, namely Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and SVM, were evaluated across different metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. The results indicate that all three models had similar performance across these metrics, with Logistic Regression and Random Forest slightly outperforming SVM, particularly in terms of F1-score. While SVM has its advantages such as its ability to handle high-dimensional data and its robustness to outliers, Logistic Regression offers better interpretability, faster training time, and ease of implementation. Therefore, depending on the specific requirements of a particular problem, one may choose Logistic Regression or Random Forest over SVM for better performance and ease of implementation.
